0","1439":"1439","1505":"1505","1427":"1427","1405":"1405","Dublin, Ireland":"Dublin, Irland","Isle of Man":"Isle of Man","County Donegal, Ireland":"County Donegal, Irland"},"nl":{"1413–1452":"1413–1452","1427–1505":"1427–1505","1405–1460":"1405–1460","1380–1439":"1380–1439","1393–1485":"1393–1485","from 1439 to 1452":"van 1439 to 1452","1413":"1413","1452":"1452","1485":"1485","1460":"1460","1393":"1393","1380":"1380","1439":"1439","1505":"1505","1427":"1427","1405":"1405","Dublin, Ireland":"Dublin, Ierland","Isle of Man":"Man","County Donegal, Ireland":"County Donegal, Ierland"},"en":{"1413–1452":"1413–1452","1427–1505":"1427–1505","1405–1460":"1405–1460","1380–1439":"1380–1439","1393–1485":"1393–1485","from 1439 to 1452":"from 1439 to 1452","1413":"1413","1452":"1452","1485":"1485","1460":"1460","1393":"1393","1380":"1380","1439":"1439","1505":"1505","1427":"1427","1405":"1405","Dublin, Ireland":"Dublin, Ireland","Isle of Man":"Isle of Man","County Donegal, Ireland":"County Donegal, Ireland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"O'Donnell,","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Brigid, Niall, Siobhan, Brennan, Bridie, Declan, Donal, Fergus, Jarlath, John Patrick, Padraic.","Irish (Donegal, Munster): Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Domhnaill</b> ‘descendant of <i>Domhnall</i>’, an old personal name composed of the Celtic elements <i>domno-</i> ‘world’ + <i>val-</i> ‘might, rule’. Compare the Anglicized form   Donald   and the Scottish clan name   McDonald  .","History: The O'Donnells, like the O'Neills (see   O'Neill  ), claim descent from Niall of the Nine Hostages (Niall Noígíallach), a legendary 5th-century king of Ireland. Their traditional base is Tyrconnell (i.e. Donegal)."],"variants":[{"name":"O'Donell","meanings":["Irish: variant of   O'Donnell  ."]},{"name":"O'Donnel","meanings":["Irish: variant of   O'Donnell  ."]},{"name":"O'Daniel","meanings":["Irish: variant of   O'Donnell  , influenced by the Biblical name   Daniel  , to which it is etymologically unrelated."]},{"name":"O'Donald","meanings":["Irish: Scotticized form of   O'Donnell  . The Irish personal name <i>Domhnall</i> was Latinized as <i>Donaldus</i>, which is the source of <i>Donald</i>, the form of the personal name used in English in Scotland, though not in Ireland. The form <i>O'Donald</i> is therefore a 19th-century hybrid. Compare   Donald  ."]},{"name":"Donald","meanings":["Scottish: shortened form of   McDonald   (<i>Mac Dhomhnaill</i>), from the Gaelic personal name <i>Domhnall</i>; found in 13th- and 14th-century Scotland as <i>Dofnald</i>, <i>Douenald</i>, <i>Dufenald</i>, and <i>Donald</i>.","Irish (Ulster): possibly also a shortened and altered form of Irish   O'Donell  ."]}]},{"name":"Naughton","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Anglicized form of the Gaelic name <i>Neachdann</i>, a derivative of <i>necht</i> ‘pure’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Naughton O'Donnell, King of Tyrconnell was born in 1413, in County Donegal, Ireland, his father, Niall Garbh O'Donnell, King of Tyrconnell, was 34 and his mother, Fionnguala  Flay O'Connor, was 20. He had at least 1 son with Nuala O'Conner. He died in 1452, at the age of 39."},"et":{"1413–1452":"1413–1452","1427–1505":"1427–1505","1405–1460":"1405–1460","1380–1439":"1380–1439","1393–1485":"1393–1485","from 1439 to 1452":"1439 kuni 1452","1413":"1413","1452":"1452","1485":"1485","1460":"1460","1393":"1393","1380":"1380","1439":"1439","1505":"1505","1427":"1427","1405":"1405","Dublin, Ireland":"Dublin, Iirimaa","Isle of Man":"Mani saar","County Donegal, Ireland":"County Donegal, Iirimaa"},"fi":{"1413–1452":"1413–1452","1427–1505":"1427–1505","1405–1460":"1405–1460","1380–1439":"1380–1439","1393–1485":"1393–1485","from 1439 to 1452":"vuodesta 1439 vuoteen 1452","1413":"1413","1452":"1452","1485":"1485","1460"